<span id="freeTextContainer17895671715856965066">Better known as &quot;Strait is the Gate&quot;. <b>4½</b>★<br/><br/>This is the second French classic I have read translated by Walter Ballenberger. I appreciate the way he has put them into modern English without losing the flavor of France. <br/><br/>I have only read one other book by Andre Gide, &quot;The Immoralist&quot;. Both that novel and this one deal with people who choose to live their lives according to a guiding principle and where that decision takes them. While I could understand the main character in &quot;The Immoralist&quot; better, I</span>
  <span id="freeText17895671715856965066" style="display:none">Better known as "Strait is the Gate". <b>4½</b>★<br /><br />This is the second French classic I have read translated by Walter Ballenberger. I appreciate the way he has put them into modern English without losing the flavor of France. <br /><br />I have only read one other book by Andre Gide, "The Immoralist". Both that novel and this one deal with people who choose to live their lives according to a guiding principle and where that decision takes them. While I could understand the main character in "The Immoralist" better, I had more sympathy for Alissa &amp; Jerome in this novel.<br /><br />Both are quite short and would make a good introduction to this Nobel Laureate.</span>
