<span id="freeTextContainer7081954897890563238">I was interested to read in the reviews that this book should be read with L&apos;Immoraliste. That was an excellent idea, which strengthened my impression that people (men? I only know of Hesse in this category but maybe there are also women) brought up as extremely strict Protestants tend to discover what Gide calls les nourritures terrestres and to spend their lives lurching between the latter and a longing for inhuman asceticism. La Porte Étroite, which seems incredible in our day, presents us wi</span>
  <span id="freeText7081954897890563238" style="display:none">I was interested to read in the reviews that this book should be read with L'Immoraliste. That was an excellent idea, which strengthened my impression that people (men? I only know of Hesse in this category but maybe there are also women) brought up as extremely strict Protestants tend to discover what Gide calls les nourritures terrestres and to spend their lives lurching between the latter and a longing for inhuman asceticism. La Porte Étroite, which seems incredible in our day, presents us with the ascetic end of the spectrum and so I would recommend it anyone wishing to understand Gide's personal dilemma. To be read before or after L'immoraliste!</span>
