        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3069180903" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15279836575220388107">This is a beautifully written soap opera.<br/><img src='https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1491734697ra/22440792.gif' height='300' width='400&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;This was a big disappointment! I was so excited for this book. Andre Gide is one of the most important and most influential French authors, so I had high hopes. &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;But the writing was beautiful and it makes me want to pick up more of his works. Honestly, the main reason I didn’t like this book was because it felt like a soap opera.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;Spoilers Below!&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;We have the protagonist who is deeply in love with his cousin (Alissa). Squirmy material, but given the time period it was somewhat normal. &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;img src=' class='gr-hostedUserImg'/><br/><br/>So the narrator and Alissa have been in love with each other since they were young. But despite this overwhelming love for one another, Alissa seems flaky. She says she loves him but pushes him away for one reason or another. It comes out that she is the type of person who would make sacrifices for the sake of others, and she does this despite knowing the hurt it causes the narrator.<br/><br/><a href='https://thescientificdetective.wordpress.com/2019/12/21/strait-is-the-gate-by-andre-gide-translated-by-dorothy-bussy-book-review/' target='blank' rel='nofollow noopener'>Review Continued Here</a> <br/></span>
